This is a blog post about ordinal numbers,
ordinal arithmetic,
and a brief advertisement for a result
I proved with Beth Branman, [George Domat](https://sites.google.com/view/georgedomat/home), and [Hannah Hoganson](https://www.math.umd.edu/~hoganson/).
We're hoping to put a paper on the arXiv and submit for publication in the coming weeks;
I'll update this post with a link when it's up.

## Nuh-uh! Infinity plus one!

I'm sure you've probably spent enough time
with children or were once a child to remember
a variant of the line above.
Somehow you and a friend are competing to name bigger
and bigger numbers.
Maybe your friend thinks they've won
because they know about infinity and say "Infinity!"
and you _have_ to top that, so you say
"Nuh-uh! Infinity _plus one!_"
At a vibes level, ordinal numbers in mathematics are a way to actually take that idea seriously.

## Two definitions

A _totally ordered set_ is a set [`S`]($mathtex)
with an order [`>`]($mathtex);
given any two distinct elements [`x`]($mathtex) and [`y`]($mathtex) of the set, one is always bigger,
maybe [`x`]($mathtex) is bigger, so we say [`x > y`]($mathtex). The order is transitive as usual.

Some total orders go on forever in one or both directions.
For example, the integers [`\mathbb{Z}`]($mathtex). 
Given an integer like 16, there's always an element smaller than it, and an element bigger than it.
A set is _well-ordered_ if it only goes on forever as you get bigger.
That is, a set is _well-ordered_ if any nonempty subset has a smallest element.

So the integers are not well-ordered, but the _natural numbers_ [`\mathbb{N} = \{0,1,2,\ldots\}`]($mathtex) are well-ordered.

An _ordinal_ is the order-isomorphism class of a well-ordered set.

The _von Neumann_ definition of the ordinals provides a convenient (although initially very confusing because the quickest way to say it gets circular fast) way to represent ordinals:

We start with [`\mathbf{0} = \varnothing`]($mathtex). The empty set is the zero ordinal.
Next [`\mathbf{1} = \{\mathbf{0}\} = \{\varnothing\}`]($mathtex). The set containing the empty set is the first successor ordinal.
In general, given an ordinal [`\alpha`]($mathtex), there is an ordinal [`\alpha + 1`]($mathtex) which, as a set, is the collection of all ordinals up to and including [`\alpha`]($mathtex) in the order that they appear.
So for example [`\mathbf{2} = \mathbf{1} + 1 = \{\mathbf{0}, \mathbf{1}\}`]($mathtex).

In this definition, each ordinal is a prefix of all ordinals which are bigger than it.
Given an increasing sequence of ordinals [`\{\alpha_n\}_{n \in \mathbb{N}}`]($mathtex), their union is a well-ordered set which we call [`\lim_{n\to\infty}\alpha_n`]($mathtex). The first example is
[`\mathbb{N} = \omega = \lim_{n\to\infty} \mathbf{n}`]($mathtex). The notation [`\omega`]($mathtex) is standard when referring to the set of natural numbers as an ordinal, so we'll use it throughout this post.

Notice, this definition makes it totally sensible to say [`\omega + 1 = \omega \cup \{\omega\} = \mathbb{N} \cup \{\omega\}`]($mathtex)!
Here is a picture representing [`\omega + 1`]($mathtex).

